### **Standing Rock: The Dakota Access Pipeline Fight — Full Story (Plain English)**

The **Standing Rock protests** (2016–2017) were a massive stand by the **Standing Rock Sioux Tribe** against the **Dakota Access Pipeline (DAPL)** — a 1,200-mile oil line from North Dakota to Illinois. It threatened their water, sacred sites, and treaty rights. This became a **global symbol** of Indigenous resistance, drawing 10,000+ people and spotlighting **UNDRIP** and **FPIC** failures.<grok:render card_id="5e47da" card_type="citation_card" type="render_inline_citation">
<argument name="citation_id">1</argument>
</grok:render><grok:render card_id="cb8e85" card_type="citation_card" type="render_inline_citation">
<argument name="citation_id">7</argument>
</grok:render>

---

#### **What Was the Project?**
- **DAPL**: Built by Energy Transfer Partners (ETP) to carry 570,000 barrels of oil/day from Bakken fields (North Dakota) under the Missouri River (drinking water for 17 million people).
- **Route**: Passed <1 mile from Standing Rock Reservation, under **Lake Oahe** (Missouri River dammed part).
- **Cost**: $3.8 billion; started 2014, finished 2017.
- **Why?**: Faster, cheaper than original Keystone route.

---

#### **Why the Tribe Opposed It**
- **Water Threat**: A spill could poison the Missouri — their main drinking source, used for fishing/ceremonies.
- **Sacred Sites**: Pipeline crossed burial grounds and prayer sites; construction bulldozed them.
- **Treaty Rights**: Violated **1851 Treaty of Fort Laramie** (guarantees "undisturbed" land) and **1868 Treaty** (Sioux sovereignty).<grok:render card_id="a6dc30" card_type="citation_card" type="render_inline_citation">
<argument name="citation_id">0</argument>
</grok:render><grok:render card_id="f71ebf" card_type="citation_card" type="render_inline_citation">
<argument name="citation_id">1</argument>
</grok:render>
- **No Consent**: Tribe said **NO** early, but ignored.

---

